Statistical Machine Learning with R

Big Data Ignite 2018 - WMRUG Session

Introduction

There are many advanced statistical machine learning techniques available from R which are best addressed individually, not briefly touched on in a 40 minute introduction. In order to lay some groundwork for those, we will take a brief look at some of the most basic statistical machine learning techniques implemented in R. As time permits we will look at:

  • Linear regression
  • Logistic regression (including ROC curves)
  • Linear and Quadratic Discriminant Analysis
  • Support Vector Machines

‘Some of the code and figures in this presentation are taken from “An Introduction to Statistical Learning, with applications in R” (Springer, 2013) with permission from the authors: G. James, D. Witten, T. Hastie and R. Tibshirani’
http://www-bcf.usc.edu/~gareth/ISL/index.html

Regression

Regression is a form of supervised estimation that finds numerical values for model parameters. As we’ll see with the logistic form of regression, the resulting numerical values can be used to classify observations allowing regression to also serve as a classifier.

Linear modeling (the general term for regression) is a subset of the model mentioned above were the function f is \(f(\vec{x}) = A\vec{x} + \epsilon\). It is a supervised estimation technique. The observations of the left side of the equation or dependent variable(s) are paired with those of the right or independenet variables and we estimate the entries of that matrix A. The end result is a simple linear equation allowing us to predict values of the dependent variable(s).

That the ‘linear’ limitation isn’t much of a limitation. Any function can be approximated by a polynomial, allowing linear modeling to fit arbitrarily complex models, we just need the data.

Simple Linear Regression

Predict the value of a single quantitative dependent variable using a single quantitative independent variable.

Boston is data for 506 tracts of the Boston suburbs with aggregate statistics for each. Model median value of owner occupied homes ($1000’s) by status of population.

The Stock Market Data

Logistic Regression

Fitting a binary dependent variable with a quantitative independent variable, i.e. classification. For example the liklihood of loan default based on the loan balance, or here the liklihood of a market rise given recent market movements.

Let’s try predicting the direction of the stock market based on information available in the Smarket data set.

That gives us a little over a 50% chance of prediction success. About as good as flipping a coin.

But that’s testing the model against the same data it was fit with. The real test is to fit the model (train it) on past data and apply it to new data. We’ll do that be fitting using data prior to 2005 and then testing it on the data from 2005 to see how good the predictions are.

Fit the logistic model using the last 5 lags and volume against the training data.

Make predictions from the 2005 data using a cut point of 0.5.

How did we do?

##         Direction
## glm.pred Down Up
##     Down   77 97
##     Up     34 44
## 
## Chance of prediction success: 0.4801587

Not so hot… flipping a coin would have done as well.

## Correct:  0.4801587
## Errors:  0.5198413

Those last two are the success rate and the error rates… not too good. This is strictly a technical analysis, let’s talk about fundamentals.

Try cutting back to just the first two lags.

##         Direction
## glm.pred Down  Up
##     Down   35  35
##     Up     76 106
## [1] 0.5595238
## [1] 0.5824176
##         1         2 
## 0.4791462 0.4960939

The overall success rate is only about 56%. If we just look at days the model predicts an up market, it’s correct about 58% of the time (want to bet on that?). Last calculation was a specific pair of predictions, just to show how we can make them from the model.

ROC Curve

We’ve been using confusion matrices and success rates to evaluate model performance. A more sophisticated evaluation is to use the ROC or Receiver Operating Characteristic curve. It plots the true positive (sensitivity) result rate versus the false positive (1-specificity) rate.

Support Vector Machine

The Support Vector Classifier is similar to a linear discriminant analysis in that it uses a linear hyperplane to separate the data. A more powerful approach is to allow non-linear kernels. We’ll take a look at the radial kernel.
